content: Sit-to-stand (chair squats): This fundamental movement directly translates to daily life - getting out of a chair, off the toilet, or up from the bed. It strengthens quadriceps, glutes, and core muscles while practicing balance during transitions. For older adults, maintaining the ability to stand up independently is critical for autonomy. Start with a higher chair or use armrests if needed. As you get stronger, progress to a lower chair or add a brief pause at the bottom.
sourceTitle: Functional Movement Explanations - Sit to Stand

content: Single-leg balance: Standing on one leg is essential for walking (every step is briefly single-leg), navigating uneven surfaces, and recovering from stumbles. This exercise strengthens hip stabilizers and ankle muscles while training proprioception (body awareness in space). Start by holding a wall or chair, progress to light touch, then hands-free, then eyes closed. Even 10 seconds per leg daily can significantly improve fall prevention.

Heel-to-toe walk (tandem walk): This balance exercise mimics tightrope walking and challenges lateral stability. It's crucial for navigating narrow spaces like crowded rooms or getting in and out of a car. This movement strengthens ankle stabilizers and improves coordination. Practice along a wall for safety. It's normal to wobble - that wobbling is your balance system working and improving!

Wall push-ups: Upper body pushing strength is essential for getting up from the floor, pushing open heavy doors, and maintaining posture. Wall push-ups are a safe regression that builds chest, shoulder, and tricep strength without loading the wrists or requiring floor work. They also engage the core for stability. Progress by moving your feet farther from the wall, then eventually progress to countertop or floor push-ups.

Step-ups: Climbing stairs is a key functional movement for independence. Step-ups build quadriceps, glutes, and hip flexor strength while practicing balance during transitions. Start with a low step (4-6 inches) and use a railing for support. Focus on pressing through the front heel and stepping all the way up without push-off from the back leg. This movement also builds cardiovascular endurance and bone density in the hips.

Seated marching: For those with balance limitations or when starting out, seated marching builds hip flexor strength and core engagement without fall risk. This movement is essential for walking, lifting knees when climbing stairs, and getting in and out of cars. It can be progressed by adding a resistance band, increasing tempo, or eventually standing. Every movement counts, even seated ones!
